vote in the same elections that the voter would otherwise be entitled to vote but for the
voter's detention.
(f) To the maximum extent feasible, voting booths and screens must be provided
to ensure the voter's right to a private ballot.
(g) All provisions of this title applicable to poll watchers apply to a satellite voting
location under this section, subject to approval by the county election commission.
(h) If feasible and if in the jail's or detention facility's possession, the jail or
detention facility shall provide the incarcerated voter with access to the voter's
identification sufficient under ยง 2-7-112 to vote at the jail satellite voting location. If it is
not feasible for the jail or detention facility to provide the identification, or if it is not in the
jail's or detention facility's possession, the jail or detention facility shall make available
jail records containing the voter's name and photograph to serve as evidence of
identification, as provided in ยง 2-7-112(c)(8).
(i) This section does not prohibit an individual from voting during the early voting
period at another location established for early voting, voting in person on election day at
their designated precinct, or voting absentee by mail, unless the person has voted in jail
or a detention facility pursuant to this section.
(j) The county election commission shall collaborate with the sheriff to facilitate
voter registration for eligible voters detained at the jail or detention facility. The jail or
detention facility shall provide a voter registration application to a person in custody at
the jail or detention facility who requests an application.
(k) Each jail and detention facility in the county shall make available printed
current resource materials, maintained by the county election commission and the
secretary of state, containing detailed information regarding the voting rights of a person
with a criminal conviction and the process for restoring one's right to vote if it has been
lost due to a criminal conviction.
